@article{bau2014cultural,
	Abstract = {In this paper, I show that cultural norms impact parents' human capital investment in their children through strategic channels. I test whether norms which increase parents' ability to capture the returns on their investments in their children are associated with greater human capital investment. Using difference-in-differences, I exploit within-country variation in ethnic norms that affect the probability that a parent can capture the returns on investment in a child of a given gender or birth order. I show that norms that increase the probability that a child supports his or her parents in their old age increase school enrollment in Ghana, Indonesia, Mexico, and Rwanda. Triple- differences results are consistent with the fact that this effect is driven by strategic considerations. The creation of pension plans has a greater negative impact on investment in children who are more likely to support their parents. Lower maternal mortality differentially increases investment in female children who are more likely to support their parents. These results also suggest one possible mechanism for positive male bias in human capital investment since males remain with parents after marriage more often than females in traditional cultures.},
